content:
&ldquo;Of course&rdquo; is a funny phrase. It simultaneously dismisses and acknowledges: &ldquo;Of course they said that.&rdquo; Like, &ldquo;We see you, but we don&rsquo;t want to see you.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Of course they support social justice dogma.&rdquo; is a knee-jerk reaction we might be tempted to make, and one that will quickly make us jerks.
We might, however, say the exact same words, to a different effect if we say them non-sarcastically &ndash; earnestly, compassionately, invitingly.

If you&rsquo;ve recognized at least a little SJD Acolyte in yourself, like we&rsquo;ve seen in ourselves, you might be met with a mix of emotions. Like feeling guilty or embarrassed or ashamed.
We&rsquo;ve looked back on workshops we led, things we&rsquo;ve written, ways we&rsquo;ve interacted online with a new lens, and seen dogmatic or fundamentalist notes where before we only thought we were doing the &ldquo;right thing.&rdquo;
Sometimes it&rsquo;s not a mix of emotions, but a simple &ldquo;Oops. Wish I knew better. I won&rsquo;t be doing that again.&rdquo;
This same range is possible for anyone in our lives we notice playing the role of SJD Acolyte.

To the social justice person who only knows SJD, an acolyte who reinforces the dogma every chance that arises, what might happen if we say:
 &ldquo;What an amazing student of SJD you have been. You care about the oppressed, and ending oppression. You speak up when you&rsquo;re told it&rsquo;s the right thing to do, and otherwise you pass the mic. You embrace the paradoxes and take risks for a more just world. You know exactly what to say and what not to say. You&rsquo;ve become fluent in a new language and internalized the acceptable actions, attitudes, and beliefs with amazing fidelity. You&rsquo;ve learned so much.&rdquo;
 And we mean it?

If any of those recaps felt dubious to you, we suggest you revisit that Module, and jump into the related Community section to discuss them. Ask questions, take time, whatever you need.
We want to make sure we&rsquo;re standing on similar ground &ndash; and able to avoid &ldquo;standing our ground.&rdquo;
The importance of self-reflection, mindfulness, and patience (with ourselves and others) is ever-increasing throughout this course, and in this Module all of that will be tested.
